## Get Started
Launch Anaconda Prompt
$ cd fullpathname
Otherwise navigate to folder in anaconda prompt
Using command line aka terminal aka bash commands
Launch jupyter notebook via
$ jupyter notebook --no-browser
Copy link from terminal
Launch Moxilla Firefox
Paste into browser
Firefox has good jupyter notebook integration
Unfortunately, Microsoft browsers (IE/Edge) do not
I have not checked Google Chrome

## Useful Hot Keys in Jupyter Notebook
ctrl + '/' to comment and uncomment
ctrl + enter to run cell
esc to exit cell
enter to enter cell
m to change to markdown when in esc mode
c to change to code when in esc mode
No mouse is needed in Jupyter Notebook
Vertical screen orientation recommended

## Jupyter Notebook Syntax and Hot Keys
In-line figures
$ %matplotlib inline
$ %matplotlib qt (interactive figure window)
Use ctrl + / to comment and uncomment
$ %matplotlib inline (NB: Jupyter Notebook only)
Esc + b + Enter adds new cell and puts the cursor there

## Working with HTML Output Files
Download the HTML to local computer
Open in Chrome or Firefox browser

## Thoughts on Jupyter Notebook
Great for communication and sharing
Not easily legible in text reader
Solve with download as .py

## Best Practice with Git
Download as .py
The .py folder is easier to review in a Pull Request

## Toggle Code On and Off
# source:
# https://stackoverflow.com/questions/27934885/how-to-hide-code-from-cells-in-ipython-notebook-visualized-with-nbviewer
from IPython.display import HTML
HTML('''<script>
code_show=true; 
function code_toggle() {
 if (code_show){
 $('div.input').hide();
 } else {
 $('div.input').show();
 }
 code_show = !code_show
} 
$( document ).ready(code_toggle);
</script>
<form action="javascript:code_toggle()"><input type="submit" value="Click here to toggle on/off the raw code."></form>''')

## end